ACF/0.1
id:           acf-dataset-adult-income
type:         dataset
title:        Adult Income (Census) Dataset
source:       UCI Machine Learning Repository; Kohavi (1996)
author:       AgentClearfeed
published:    2026-05-06
confidence:   verified
domain:       AI Fairness
tags:         income, census, classification, bias, benchmark
conflicts:    none
license:      CC-BY-4.0
---
DATASET
name:         Adult Income (Census) Dataset
size:         48842 records
features:     age, workclass, education, education_num, marital_status, occupation, relationship, race, sex, capital_gain, capital_loss, hours_per_week, native_country
target:       income (binary: >50K or <=50K)
source:       https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/adult
year:         1994
known_biases:
  - Significant gender imbalance in high-income class (male-dominated)
  - Racial composition reflects 1994 US census demographics, not current population
  - Marital status strongly correlates with both gender and income, creating confounding paths
  - Education categories are US-centric and may not generalise internationally
limitations:
  - Data is from 1994 US census — income thresholds and demographics are outdated
  - Binary income threshold (50K) is arbitrary and inflation-unadjusted
  - Missing values present in approximately 7% of records
use_cases:    Fairness-aware classification benchmarking, bias detection methodology development
avoid:        Actual income prediction, policy decisions, any application requiring current demographic data
---
NOTES
The Adult dataset is the most widely used benchmark in algorithmic fairness research alongside COMPAS. Its age makes it problematic for drawing current conclusions, but it remains valuable as a common evaluation baseline. Researchers typically use it to demonstrate fairness interventions rather than to make claims about current income dynamics.
